1. Description of Plan
The following description of the State Farm Insurance Companies Retirement Plan for United States Employees (the
“Plan”) is provided for general information purposes only. Members should refer to the Plan document for more
complete information.
The Plan is a noncontributory, defined benefit plan. State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance Company
(“SFMAIC”) is the Plan Sponsor. Employees of SFMAIC and several of its subsidiaries participate in the Plan. The
SFMAIC subsidiaries currently participating in the Plan are State Farm Fire and Casualty Company, State Farm Life
Insurance Company, State Farm Life and Accident Assurance Company, State Farm General Insurance Company,
State Farm Indemnity Company, State Farm VP Management Corporation, State Farm Florida Insurance Company
and State Farm International Holding Company (collectively known as the “Company” or “Companies”). The Plan is
subject to the provisions of the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974 (“ERISA”).
The Board of Directors of SFMAIC has delegated to its Compensation Committee the responsibility for all ERISA
‘settlor’ (i.e., “Plan Sponsor”) functions. Therefore, the Compensation Committee has adopted the State Farm
Employee Retirement Trust (“Trust”), as required by ERISA.
The Pension Administrative Committee (“PAC”) is the Plan Administrator. The Board of Directors of SFMAIC has
delegated to the PAC all fiduciary responsibilities pertaining to operation of the Plan.
The Board of Directors of SFMAIC has delegated to its Finance and Investment Committee the responsibility for
the investment plan/policy for the Plan. The Finance and Investment Committee has delegated responsibility for
implementation and monitoring of the investment plan/policy to the Pension Investment Committee (“PIC”).
The Board of Directors of SFMAIC has named Trustees for the Trust, who are directed and monitored by the PIC.
The Trustees hold legal title to all Trust assets, as required by ERISA. Trustees are responsible for monitoring the
Trust assets and operations. Trustees have no discretionary investment management authority or control over Trust
assets and report on their work to the PIC.
Effective January 1, 2021, newly hired employees are not eligible to participate in the Plan. Employees who rehire or
otherwise become an employee after December 31, 2020, are not eligible to accrue credited service under the Plan.
All other employees continue to accrue benefits as described below.
A. Benefits
Retirement Benefits
Employees hired or rehired prior to January 1, 2021 become members on the day they reach their 21st birthday
and complete one year of service. Active members will have a fully vested interest in retirement benefits upon
completion of five years of service after age 18 or at age 65, whichever comes first. Plan benefits are determined
by a formula based on average annual compensation, credited service and Social Security covered compensation.
Normal retirement under the Plan is the first day of the month following the member’s 65th birthday. The Plan
permits early retirement reduced benefits on the first day of any month after age 55 and before the employee’s
62nd birthday. There is no reduction in benefits for early retirement at ages 62 through 64. Employees may elect
any one of four different benefit payment options – life income; life income with 10 years certain; joint life
income with ⅔ to survivor (for effective date of retirement on or before December 1, 2007) or joint life income
to survivor (for effective date of retirement after December 1, 2007); or life income with ¾ to surviving spouse
(for effective date of retirement on or before December 1, 2007) or life income with ½ to surviving beneficiary
(for effective date of retirement after December 1, 2007). If the present value of the accrued benefit does not
exceed $7,000 ($5,000 prior to January 1, 2024) in the month of distribution, the value will be paid in one lump
sum. Effective January 1, 2024, the default option for distributions greater than $1,000 but less than $7,000

($5,000 prior to January 1, 2024) is direct rollover to an IRA. Employees terminating without a vested interest in
their accrued retirement benefit will forfeit all benefits.
Death Benefits
Survivor income is available upon the death of any active (not in receipt of retirement income), inactive or
disabled member who has a vested interest. Survivor benefits are paid to the member’s spouse or beneficiary. If
there is a qualified spouse, payments are made for the life of the qualified spouse with five years certain. If there
is no qualified spouse, payments are made to the spouse or other named contingent (individual) beneficiary for
five years. Should the beneficiary die prior to completion of the five-year period, the unpaid remainder is paid in
one lump sum to the beneficiary’s estate. If the contingent beneficiary is not an individual, survivor benefits will
be paid in one sum. If the member does not have a spouse at the time of death and has not named a contingent
beneficiary, survivor benefits will be paid in one lump sum to the member’s estate or legal representative. The
amount of the survivor benefit will be calculated based on the amount that would have been paid to a joint
annuitant under the joint life income with ⅔ to survivor retirement income option (for deaths on or before
December 31, 2007) or joint life income with ¾ to survivor retirement income option (for deaths after December
31, 2007).
For deaths after October 1, 2008, the life income with 5 years certain benefit is payable to a qualified spouse or
another individual beneficiary. If the survivor income is payable to multiple beneficiaries, the present value of the
life income with 5 years certain benefit is divided equally among the beneficiaries and paid as a single lump sum.
Disability Benefits
If a member becomes disabled while actively employed by one of the Companies, the member may elect to
receive disability income or to accrue additional credited service during the period of disability. The amount of
each disability income payment will be 1⁄12 of the normal annual retirement income accrued in the Plan as of the
date disability income is first payable. Payment of disability income or accrual of additional credited service will
cease on the earliest of death, retirement or reaching normal retirement date, recovery from total disability, or
when eligibility for Social Security benefits ceases.
B. Contributions
All contributions are paid by SFMAIC to the Trustees. No contributions are required or permitted from any Plan
member. The contributions are based upon the Plan actuary’s calculation and are designed to fund the current
service costs on a current basis and to fund, over not more than seven years, any unfunded liabilities.
Minimum funding requirements of ERISA have been met or exceeded for the year ended December 31, 2024.
C. Accumulated Benefits
Accumulated plan benefits are those future periodic payments that are attributable under the Plan’s provisions to
the credited service Plan members have rendered. As of December 31, 2024 and 2023, accumulated plan benefits
are based on the highest average of the member’s annual compensation amounts for any consecutive 1,825 days
of credited service and on the member’s covered compensation. Benefits payable for retirement, death and
disability are included to the extent they are deemed attributable to credited service rendered to the valuation date.
The present value of accumulated plan benefits is the value that results from applying actuarial assumptions to
adjust the accumulated plan benefits to reflect the time value of money (through discounts of interest) and
probability of payment (by means of decrements for withdrawal, death, disability, or retirement) between the
valuation date and the expected date of payment. The accumulated plan benefits as of December 31, 2024 and
2023 were calculated by the Plan’s actuary.

D. Plan Termination
While the Companies have not expressed any intent to terminate their participation in the Plan, they are free to do
so at any time, subject to the provisions set forth under ERISA. In the event that the Plan is terminated, the
normal retirement income based upon credited service to the date of Plan termination shall become fully vested
and non-forfeitable to the extent funded based on the financial health of the plan sponsor and the level of benefits
guaranteed by the Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation. The assets of the trust fund shall be allocated in
accordance with the order for such allocation in Section 4044 of ERISA, or any successor section or statute
thereto.
2. Summary of Significant Accounting Policies
A. Basis of Accounting
The financial statements of the Plan are prepared under the accrual method of accounting in accordance with
accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America.
B. Investments
All investments are held, and investment transactions are processed by an external custodial institution
(“Custodian”).
Investments are stated at fair value. Cash held by the Plan is interest bearing and includes foreign currency
converted to U.S. dollars using quoted foreign exchange rates. United States government and agency securities,
corporate debt and other debt securities are valued at fair value based on market price quotations provided by an
independent pricing service or determined through an internal pricing matrix. Common stocks and registered
investment companies traded on securities exchanges or in the over-the-counter market are valued at the last
reported sales price for the day. Money market instruments are valued at net asset value which approximates fair
value. Forward currency contracts are valued using quoted foreign exchange rates.
Investment income on bonds and notes, common stocks and registered investment companies are recorded as
earned on an accrual basis. Bond interest includes the amortization of purchase premiums or the accretion of
purchase discounts. Dividends are recorded on the ex-dividend date. Purchases and sales of publicly traded
investments are reflected on a trade date basis, while purchases of private placement debt securities are recorded
on a settlement or funding date basis.
The Plan presents in the Statement of Changes in Net Assets Available for Benefits the net appreciation
(depreciation) in the fair value of its investments, which consists of the realized gains or losses and the unrealized
appreciation or depreciation on those investments. The net appreciation or depreciation is included in the “Net
appreciation in fair value of investments” line on the Statement of Changes in Net Assets Available for Benefits.
Gain (loss) realized on disposal is calculated as the difference between the current value of the investment and the
proceeds received on the sale date. Current value reporting is required for determining the total net gain (loss) on
the sale of assets that is reported on Schedule H of Form 5500 filed with the U.S. Department of Labor.
Currency hedging, including cross hedging, is used primarily as part of a defensive strategy to protect the
portfolio’s underlying assets. The Plan enters into forward currency contracts, which represent agreements to
exchange currencies of different countries at specific future dates at specified rates. The forward currency
contracts are used to reduce the exposure of investments denominated in non-U.S. currencies to fluctuations in
foreign exchange rates. Forward currency contracts involve market risk in excess of the amount recognized in the
Statement of Net Assets Available for Benefits.

C. Administrative and Other Expenses
Office personnel, space and equipment, actuarial, record keeping, legal and certain investment services are
furnished by the Companies at no charge to the Plan. Administrative and other expenses paid by the Plan include
custodial, investment management, consulting fees due to external third parties, foreign income tax expenses, and
investment related fees that are paid to JPMorgan Chase which is the Plan’s custodial bank and a party in interest.
In 2024 the Plan paid an annual premium in the amount of $11.7 million to the Pension Benefit Guaranty
Corporation.
D. Use of Estimates
The preparation of the Plan’s financial statements in conformity with accounting principles generally accepted in
the United States of America requires the Plan Administrator to make significant estimates and assumptions that
affect the reported amounts of net assets available for benefits at the date of the financial statements and the
accumulated plan benefits as of the benefit information date, the changes in net assets available for benefits and
the changes in the accumulated plan benefits during the reporting period and, when applicable, the disclosures of
contingent assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements. Actual results could differ from those
estimates.
E. Risks and Uncertainties
The Plan invests in various investment securities. Investment securities are exposed to various risks such as
interest rate, market, credit, and foreign currency exchange risks. Due to the level of risk associated with certain
investment securities, it is at least reasonably possible that changes in the values of investment securities will
occur in the near term and such changes could materially affect the amounts reported in the Statements of Net
Assets Available for Benefits.
Plan contributions and the accumulated plan benefits are prepared based on certain assumptions pertaining to
interest rates, inflation rates, and employee demographics, all of which are subject to change. Due to uncertainties
inherent in the estimations and assumptions process, it is at least reasonably possible that changes in these
estimates and assumptions in the near term would be material to the financial statements.
F. Benefits Paid
Benefits paid to members are recorded upon distribution.

4. Fair Value Measurements
Fair value is defined as the price that would be received upon selling an investment in a timely transaction to an
independent buyer in the principal or most advantageous market of the investment. The Plan's financial assets carried
at fair value have been classified, for disclosure purposes, based on a hierarchy which prioritizes the inputs to
valuation techniques used to measure fair value. A financial instrument’s level within the fair value hierarchy is based
on the lowest level of any input that is significant to the fair value measurement. The three levels of the fair value
hierarchy are summarized below:
Level 1 – Observable inputs that reflect unadjusted quoted prices for identical securities in active markets.
Level 2 – Observable inputs other than quoted prices included in level 1 such as quoted prices for similar
securities; interest rates, prepayment schedules and credit risk for fixed income securities; or other inputs that are
observable or can be corroborated by observable market data.
Level 3 – Unobservable inputs including the Plan’s own assumptions in determining the fair value of investments.

The following is a description of the valuation methodologies used for assets at fair value. There have been no
changes in the methodologies used at December 31, 2024 compared to December 31, 2023.
Level 1 Measurements
Level 1 assets include cash, exchange-listed equity securities or equity mutual funds, and money market mutual funds
where the net asset value is available publicly. Valuations are based upon unadjusted quoted prices.
Level 2 Measurements
Bonds - These assets include United States government and agency, corporate debt, and other debt securities valued
by an independent pricing vendor. Typical inputs to models used by pricing vendors include but are not limited to
benchmark yields, reported trades, broker/dealer quotes, issuer spreads, two-sided markets, benchmark securities,
bids, offers, and reference data including market research publications. On newly acquired publicly traded bonds not
yet priced by the pricing vendor, the purchase price is used as fair value except at year-end. For newly acquired
securities or existing securities that do not have a price at year-end, a broker quote is obtained to determine fair value.
For private placement bonds not priced by the pricing vendor, an internal pricing matrix is used to estimate fair value.
Inputs to the internal pricing matrix include benchmark yields, credit spreads, the industry sector of the issuer, and
illiquidity spreads.
Forward Currency Contracts - These assets and liabilities are valued using quoted foreign exchange rates.
5. Tax Status
The IRS has determined and informed the Plan by a letter dated January 23, 2017, that the Plan and related trust are
designed in accordance with applicable sections of the Internal Revenue Code (IRC). Although the Plan has been
amended since receiving the determination letter, the Plan administrator and the Plan's tax counsel believe that the
Plan is designed and is currently being operated in compliance with the applicable requirements of the IRC and
therefore believe that the Plan is qualified, and the related trust is tax-exempt.
Accounting principles generally accepted in the United States of America require plan management to evaluate tax
positions taken by the Plan and recognize a tax liability (or asset) if the Plan has taken an uncertain position that more
likely than not would not be sustained upon examination by the Internal Revenue Service. The Plan’s management
has reviewed the tax positions taken by the Plan and determined that as of December 31, 2024, and December 31,
2023, there are no uncertain positions taken or expected to be taken within the next 12 months that would require
recognition of a liability (or asset) or disclosure in the financial statements. The Plan is subject to audits for tax
periods within a three-year prior period; the Plan is no longer subject to income tax examinations for years prior to
2021. Currently there are no tax audits in progress for any tax periods.
6. Parties in Interest
The Companies, Plan Administrator, PIC and Trustees are parties in interest. JPMorgan Chase is the Plan’s custodian
to whom custodian fees are paid. Northern Trust (“NT”) and Capital Guardian Trust Company (“CGTC”) are
investment advisors for assets that are held at JPMorgan Chase. Alight, a defined benefit service provider, administers
the benefit payments on behalf of the Plan.
The Plan holds investments in its custodian, JPMorgan Chase, and in one of its investment advisors, Northern Trust.

The following briefly describes the key provisions of the Retirement Plan for United States Employees.
Reference should be made to the Plan Document for additional clarification and details.
Status of Plan Effective January 1, 2021 the Plan is closed to new
hires with active members continuing to earn service
and pay accruals.
Plan Year
The plan year is the calendar year.
Employee The term “Employee-agent” shall mean any individual
holding a State Farm Agent’s Employment Agreement
or a State Farm Trainee Agent Agreement dated
October 1, 1995 or later with any of the Companies.
The word ″Employee″ shall mean a person in the
employment of the Company, including Employee-
agents, special sales representatives and officers of
the Companies, but excluding the following persons:
 Any director, unless said director is otherwise
regularly employed by the Companies;
 Any person whose terms and conditions of
employment are determined by a collective
bargaining agreement between the Companies
and a labor union which does not make the
Plan applicable to them;
 Any person or agent, other than an Employee-
agent, whose remuneration from the
Companies is paid solely by means of
commissions, retainers, fees, severance pay,
retirement allowances, or any other form of
compensation other than salary;
 Any employee of a trainee agent or field
representative;
 Any leased employee performing services for the
Companies; and
 Any employee operating under a Staff
Assistance Agreement entered into on or after
January 1, 2005.

Schedule SB, Part V — Summary of Plan Provisions
The following briefly describes the key provisions of the Retirement Plan for United States Employees.
Reference should be made to the Plan Document for additional clarification and details.
Status of Plan Effective January 1, 2021 the Plan is closed to new
hires with active members continuing to earn service
and pay accruals.
Plan Year
The plan year is the calendar year.
Employee The term “Employee-agent” shall mean any individual
holding a State Farm Agent’s Employment Agreement
or a State Farm Trainee Agent Agreement dated
October 1, 1995 or later with any of the Companies.
The word ″Employee″ shall mean a person in the
employment of the Company, including Employee-
agents, special sales representatives and officers of
the Companies, but excluding the following persons:
 Any director, unless said director is otherwise
regularly employed by the Companies;
 Any person whose terms and conditions of
employment are determined by a collective
bargaining agreement between the Companies
and a labor union which does not make the
Plan applicable to them;
 Any person or agent, other than an Employee-
agent, whose remuneration from the
Companies is paid solely by means of
commissions, retainers, fees, severance pay,
retirement allowances, or any other form of
compensation other than salary;
 Any employee of a trainee agent or field
representative;
 Any leased employee performing services for the
Companies; and
 Any employee operating under a Staff
Assistance Agreement entered into on or after
January 1, 2005.

Schedule SB, line 24 — Change in Actuarial Assumptions
The funding valuation reflects the following assumption changes:
● Retirement rates, withdrawal rates, and salary scale rates were updated based on a 2023 Experience
Study.
● A change in the assumed retirement rates for terminated vested participants from 20% commence at age
55 and remainder commence at age 62 to 25% commence at age 55 and remainder commence at age 62
based on a 2023 Experience Study.
These changes were made to better reflect the anticipated plan experience. The funding assumption
changes did not reduce the funding shortfall more than the thresholds stated in the Internal Revenue Code
Section 430(h)(5), so approval of the Commissioner is not required.
